title.narrative: 1.2 QUALITY CHILD HEALTH SERVICES

description.narrative: 1.2 Increased capacity to provide equitable access to quality child health services and to improve healthy behaviours, which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, children, including newborns and adolescents, and women of reproductive age have improved and equitable access to and use of high-impact quality health interventions and improved healthy behaviors.

title.narrative: 1.2 Increased capacity to provide equitable access to quality child health services and to improve healthy behaviours

description.narrative: Despite the COVID-19 pandemic, UNICEF continued to support child health programmes at all three levels of government health structure. The immunization coverage has been maintained at the pre-pandemic level. Full immunization coverage dropped to 65 % in 2020 and increased to 78% in 2021. Effective Vaccine Management Assessment (EVMA) was carried outand noticed improvementsince the last assessment (2017) as 7 out of 9 indicators achieved the global EVMA benchmark. COVID-19 vaccination rolled out, 65% primary and 52% target population (≥18 years) received full-dose vaccine. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:20/12/2021
